problem.markdown:
>>Words embeddings replace one-hot vectors with a ______________ . Contextualized word embeddings address the problem of ______________. <<

[[
distributed representation, synonymy {{A distributed representation allows for a smaller vector size and to have more flexibility in the representation. This can be used to better reflect the semantics of the words in the vector space. The problem addressed by contextualized word embeddings is not synonymy, where multiple words may have the same meaning.}}
(distributed representation, polysemy) {{A distributed representation allows for a smaller vector size and to have more flexibility in the representation. This can be used to better reflect the semantics of the words in the vector space itself. Contextualized word embeddings mean that words with various meanings can be interpreted with the help of context.
}}
local representation, polysemy {{The one-hot vector is a local representation, which has two main disadvantages: its dimension is proportional to the vocabulary size, and it does not capture relations between words. Contextualized word embeddings mean that words with various meanings can be interpreted with the help of context.}}
local representation, synonymy {{The one-hot vector is a local representation, which has two main disadvantages: its dimension is proportional to the vocabulary size, and it does not capture relations between words. The problem addressed by contextualized word embeddings is not synonymy, where multiple words may have the same meaning.}}
]]

